## 4. CONDITIONS — The Core of QuantQL

### 4.1 Overview

```
BUY  WHEN <condition>
SELL WHEN <condition>
```

A condition is a logical expression built from:
- **Values** (indicator outputs, price fields, numbers)
- **Comparison operators** (`>`, `<`, `>=`, `<=`, `==`, `!=`)
- **Crossover operators** (`CROSSES_ABOVE`, `CROSSES_BELOW`)
- **Logical operators** (`AND`, `OR`, `NOT`)
- **Grouping** with parentheses `( ... )`

### 4.2 Values — What You Can Compare

#### Price Fields

| Name     | Maps to           | Description         |
|----------|-------------------|---------------------|
| `CLOSE`  | Current bar close  | Most commonly used  |
| `OPEN`   | Current bar open   | Gap analysis        |
| `HIGH`   | Current bar high   | Range breakout      |
| `LOW`    | Current bar low    | Support testing     |
| `VOLUME` | Current bar volume | Volume confirmation |

#### Indicator Outputs

Every indicator from Section 3 produces named values you can use directly:

```
RSI                    # current RSI value
MACD                   # MACD line value
SIGNAL                 # MACD signal line
HISTOGRAM              # MACD histogram
SMA                    # SMA value (or SMA(50) inline)
EMA                    # EMA value
DEMA, TEMA             # double/triple EMA
BB_UPPER, BB_MID, BB_LOWER
STOCH_K, STOCH_D
WILLIAMS
ADX, PLUS_DI, MINUS_DI
ATR
SLOPE
SAR, SAR_TREND
OBV
VWAP
```

#### Inline Parameterised Values

You can specify indicator params directly in conditions:

```
BUY WHEN CLOSE > SMA(200) AND EMA(10) > EMA(50)
```

This computes SMA(200), EMA(10), and EMA(50) on the fly.

#### Literal Numbers

```
BUY WHEN RSI > 30
SELL WHEN ADX < 20
BUY WHEN CLOSE > 1500.50
```

### 4.3 Comparison Operators

| Operator | Meaning                  | Example               |
|----------|--------------------------|-----------------------|
| `>`      | Greater than             | `RSI > 70`            |
| `<`      | Less than                | `RSI < 30`            |
| `>=`     | Greater than or equal    | `ADX >= 25`           |
| `<=`     | Less than or equal       | `WILLIAMS <= -80`     |
| `==`     | Equal to                 | `SAR_TREND == 1`      |
| `!=`     | Not equal to             | `SAR_TREND != -1`     |

Both sides can be any value:

```
BUY WHEN EMA > SMA              # indicator vs indicator
BUY WHEN CLOSE > BB_UPPER       # price vs indicator
BUY WHEN RSI > 30               # indicator vs number
BUY WHEN CLOSE > 2500           # price vs number
```

### 4.4 Crossover Operators

These detect the **moment** one value crosses another — not just whether it's above/below, but whether it **just became** above/below in the current bar.

| Operator          | Meaning                                           |
|-------------------|---------------------------------------------------|
| `CROSSES_ABOVE`   | Was ≤ previous bar, now > this bar                |
| `CROSSES_BELOW`   | Was ≥ previous bar, now < this bar                |

**How it works internally (bar `i`):**

```
MACD CROSSES_ABOVE SIGNAL

  previous bar:  MACD[i-1] <= SIGNAL[i-1]
  current bar:   MACD[i]   >  SIGNAL[i]
  → both must be true for CROSSES_ABOVE = true
```

**Examples:**

```
# MACD bullish crossover
MACD CROSSES_ABOVE SIGNAL

# MACD bearish crossover
MACD CROSSES_BELOW SIGNAL

# Price breaks above SMA
CLOSE CROSSES_ABOVE SMA(50)

# Stochastic golden cross
STOCH_K CROSSES_ABOVE STOCH_D

# EMA crossover
EMA(10) CROSSES_ABOVE EMA(50)

# Price crosses Bollinger
CLOSE CROSSES_BELOW BB_LOWER

# RSI exits oversold
RSI CROSSES_ABOVE 30

# +DI crosses above -DI (ADX trend start)
PLUS_DI CROSSES_ABOVE MINUS_DI
```

### 4.5 Logical Operators

| Operator | Meaning          | Precedence |
|----------|------------------|------------|
| `NOT`    | Negate condition | Highest    |
| `AND`    | Both must be true| Medium     |
| `OR`     | Either is true   | Lowest     |

**AND — All conditions must be true simultaneously:**

```
BUY WHEN RSI > 30 AND MACD CROSSES_ABOVE SIGNAL AND ADX > 25
#         ^^^^^^^^     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^     ^^^^^^^
#         cond 1       cond 2                          cond 3
#         ALL THREE must be true on the same bar
```

**OR — At least one condition must be true:**

```
SELL WHEN RSI > 70 OR MACD CROSSES_BELOW SIGNAL
#         ^^^^^^^^    ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
#         either one triggers the sell
```

**NOT — Invert a condition:**

```
BUY WHEN NOT RSI > 70 AND CLOSE > SMA(50)
# equivalent to: RSI <= 70 AND CLOSE > SMA(50)
```

**Grouping with parentheses — Override precedence:**

```
# Without parens: AND binds tighter than OR
SELL WHEN RSI > 80 OR MACD CROSSES_BELOW SIGNAL AND ADX < 20
# parsed as: RSI > 80 OR (MACD CROSSES_BELOW SIGNAL AND ADX < 20)

# With parens: force OR to group first
SELL WHEN (RSI > 80 OR MACD CROSSES_BELOW SIGNAL) AND ADX < 20
# now: (either RSI>80 or MACD cross) AND ADX must be < 20
```

### 4.6 Complex Condition Examples

```
# Multi-indicator confluence entry
BUY WHEN RSI > 30 AND RSI < 70 AND MACD CROSSES_ABOVE SIGNAL AND CLOSE > SMA(50) AND ADX > 25

# Bollinger + Volume squeeze
BUY WHEN CLOSE < BB_LOWER AND RSI < 35 AND VOLUME > 1000000

# Stochastic in oversold + trend confirmation
BUY WHEN STOCH_K < 20 AND STOCH_K CROSSES_ABOVE STOCH_D AND ADX > 20

# Parabolic SAR reversal
BUY WHEN SAR_TREND == 1 AND CLOSE > EMA(20)
SELL WHEN SAR_TREND == -1 OR CLOSE < EMA(20)

# Multi-timeframe concept (using different MA periods)
BUY WHEN EMA(10) > EMA(20) AND EMA(20) > SMA(50) AND RSI > 40

# Complex exit with take-profit override
SELL WHEN (RSI > 75 AND MACD CROSSES_BELOW SIGNAL) OR CLOSE CROSSES_BELOW SMA(50)

# Directional movement filter
BUY WHEN PLUS_DI > MINUS_DI AND PLUS_DI CROSSES_ABOVE 25 AND RSI > 30
SELL WHEN MINUS_DI > PLUS_DI OR ADX < 15
```

